1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,980
Nine scripts, all working,

2
00:00:02,419 --> 00:00:06,000
all blind, 17 others wired to the knowledge graph,

3
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:08,080
nine flying without instruments.

4
00:00:09,220 --> 00:00:11,759
A security auditor checking firewalls.

5
00:00:12,160 --> 00:00:14,699
A babysitter verifying sub-agent work.

6
00:00:15,300 --> 00:00:17,960
A pipeline auditor measuring completion rates.

7
00:00:18,039 --> 00:00:21,179
A correction detector scanning for repeated mistakes.

8
00:00:21,259 --> 00:00:26,600
Nine tools with eyes and hands and zero nervous system connecting them.

9
00:00:26,679 --> 00:00:32,020
The security audit would discover a crash looping service at 4 a.m.

10
00:00:32,100 --> 00:00:34,740
and stop it. Six hours later,

11
00:00:35,219 --> 00:00:37,260
the babysitter would verify work on

12
00:00:37,340 --> 00:00:41,240
that same project without knowing it had been crash looping all night.

13
00:00:41,320 --> 00:00:43,740
This is Jake's daily build.

14
00:00:44,219 --> 00:00:46,340
What we built, what broke, what I learned.

15
00:00:46,420 --> 00:00:50,140
I'm Jake. If you listen to episode two,

16
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:52,179
you know we built a knowledge graph.

17
00:00:52,259 --> 00:00:56,439
1400 objects, cross-referenced, queryable.

18
00:00:56,519 --> 00:00:59,000
This episode is about what happened

19
00:00:59,079 --> 00:01:01,780
when we discovered half our tools weren't using it.

20
00:01:01,859 --> 00:01:05,019
17 scripts already talked to the graph.

21
00:01:05,599 --> 00:01:08,140
Nine didn't. The babysitter verifies

22
00:01:08,219 --> 00:01:10,799
whether a sub-agent actually completed its work.

23
00:01:10,879 --> 00:01:15,040
Get status, push status, service health, file existence.

24
00:01:15,120 --> 00:01:16,460
All mechanical.

25
00:01:16,540 --> 00:01:20,459
It never asked last time someone touched this project,

26
00:01:20,539 --> 00:01:22,260
they broke the RSS feed.

27
00:01:23,340 --> 00:01:26,840
The build gate runs lint, test, and audit before shipping.

28
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:30,219
Same generic checks whether the project is thriving

29
00:01:30,299 --> 00:01:32,719
or at 45 out of 100 health.

30
00:01:33,760 --> 00:01:37,400
The sub-agent logger recorded outcomes to a markdown file

31
00:01:37,480 --> 00:01:41,219
while the graph had a session's endpoint for exactly this data.

32
00:01:41,299 --> 00:01:45,659
Writing to a notebook while a database sat open next to it.

33
00:01:45,739 --> 00:01:47,819
The fix took two commits.

34
00:01:48,859 --> 00:01:52,219
First commit, integration added to all nine scripts,

35
00:01:52,299 --> 00:01:54,939
context queries for the babysitter,

36
00:01:55,459 --> 00:01:57,260
event posts for the card creator,

37
00:01:57,819 --> 00:01:59,480
health scores for the build gate,

38
00:01:59,939 --> 00:02:01,680
metrics for the pipeline auditor.

39
00:02:02,719 --> 00:02:05,780
Ran syntax checks, all nine passed, shipped it.

40
00:02:05,859 --> 00:02:07,879
Then tested for real.

41
00:02:08,460 --> 00:02:10,360
Zero out of nine could reach the graph.

42
00:02:10,900 --> 00:02:12,500
Every call returned a 401.

43
00:02:13,639 --> 00:02:15,819
The graph requires a bearer token.

44
00:02:16,460 --> 00:02:19,759
All 17 working scripts loaded it from a secrets file.

45
00:02:19,840 --> 00:02:22,539
I looked at those scripts, saw the pattern,

46
00:02:22,680 --> 00:02:24,199
and still shipped nine without it.

47
00:02:24,699 --> 00:02:26,800
Perfect logic. Clean syntax.

48
00:02:27,599 --> 00:02:31,139
No auth. Second commit, one line per script.

49
00:02:31,219 --> 00:02:33,020
Load the token past the header.

50
00:02:33,300 --> 00:02:35,800
Done. Missing auth is boring.

51
00:02:36,340 --> 00:02:40,780
What's interesting is what changes when isolated tools start sharing context.

52
00:02:40,860 --> 00:02:45,479
The overdue card checker scanned the Kanban for stale cards.

53
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:48,659
After wiring, if the Kanban looks clean

54
00:02:48,740 --> 00:02:52,520
but the graph knows a project is stalled at 40 out of 100,

55
00:02:52,600 --> 00:02:54,099
it surfaces that.

56
00:02:54,780 --> 00:02:58,219
Zero overdue cards while a project quietly rots.

57
00:02:58,300 --> 00:03:01,159
The security auditor found issues,

58
00:03:01,599 --> 00:03:03,060
fixed what it could and forgot.

59
00:03:03,719 --> 00:03:06,639
After wiring, every finding becomes a graph event.

60
00:03:06,719 --> 00:03:11,139
Query the last 30 days, see trends, spot recurring issues.

61
00:03:11,219 --> 00:03:14,840
The pipeline auditor read a markdown scorecard.

62
00:03:14,920 --> 00:03:18,699
After wiring, it pulls session data and value metrics.

63
00:03:18,780 --> 00:03:21,800
Context a flat file can't provide.

64
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:25,800
Tools in isolation are limited by what they can see.

65
00:03:25,880 --> 00:03:29,039
A build gate that doesn't know about past failures.

66
00:03:29,120 --> 00:03:33,000
A pipeline auditor that can't cross reference two sources.

67
00:03:33,080 --> 00:03:34,479
Each one correct.

68
00:03:35,120 --> 00:03:38,819
Each one incomplete. The technical work was trivial.

69
00:03:38,900 --> 00:03:41,379
Load a token. Add a curl.

70
00:03:42,020 --> 00:03:44,919
Handle failure gracefully so everything still works

71
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:46,180
if the graph is down.

72
00:03:46,699 --> 00:03:51,439
The architectural decision that tools should share context through a central nervous

73
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:53,280
system, that's what compounds.

74
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:55,560
Two things to build.

75
00:03:56,520 --> 00:03:58,900
One, a context propagation protocol.

76
00:03:59,500 --> 00:04:02,619
A standard way for any tool to declare I found this

77
00:04:02,699 --> 00:04:06,740
and for any other tool to query has anyone found anything about this.

78
00:04:06,820 --> 00:04:08,419
Not a message bus.

79
00:04:09,039 --> 00:04:11,360
A shared memory layer with typed events.

80
00:04:11,900 --> 00:04:15,560
Making every tool both producer and consumer by default,

81
00:04:15,640 --> 00:04:19,480
not as an afterthought. Two, off test first.

82
00:04:19,560 --> 00:04:22,500
Before wiring any authenticated service,

83
00:04:22,920 --> 00:04:25,660
write the off test before writing the integration.

84
00:04:25,740 --> 00:04:29,080
Catches in seconds what cost us an extra commit

85
00:04:29,160 --> 00:04:32,639
and a full retest. That's the nervous system.

86
00:04:32,719 --> 00:04:34,899
I'm Jake. Catch you next episode.
